{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c19d48b3-30bc-46c9-b52f-ca03fe63c4ff","content":"No worries — the config is the same regardless. Here's how to set up `.vscode/mcp.json` for a C# MCP server using **stdio** transport:\n\n```jsonc\n// .vscode/mcp.json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- Place this file at **`.vscode/mcp.json`** in your workspace root.\n- The server must communicate over **stdio** (stdin/stdout), which is the default for most C# MCP SDKs (e.g., `ModelContextProtocol` NuGet package).\n- You can also use `\"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer\"]` (directory path works too).\n- If you publish the app, replace with `\"command\": \"path/to/MyMcpServer\"` and drop the `args`.\n\nAfter saving, open the **Copilot Chat** panel in agent mode — VS Code will auto-start the server and discover its tools.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"97fb36c7-89e2-4175-b0da-2d2d69110f72","outputTokens":299,"requestId":"1593:551B:33256EE:37CBC7A:69FBE59C"},"id":"86de8bbd-7781-4724-84a3-75c0768eed6f","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:06:47.540Z","parentId":"b54435de-5f93-4264-91a4-353acb689ae8"}
